caption: We came to South Loop Club with a party of 6. When we got there they told us that they only had a  table for 2 available, there were several tables open including a large table. They told us the large table was reserved so we asked if we could split the party up he told us there wasnt any other tables available. We decided to order food to go. While we were waiting on our order a party of 5 white people came in and they were seated with no problem. We were literally standing right there and heard the conversation so I know they didn’t have a reservation and just walked in off the street. When we asked why they were seated he tried to say they had a reservation and we clearly heard the conversation and knew that they did not. There were no other black people in the restaurant, the rest of my party and I felt like they didn’t want us to dine in because we were a group of black people.

Some of my friends and I decided to go to this place (we have even been here before) but one of my friends had an international ID so they didn't let us in. After waiting for his cab to arrive, we entered the place but for some reason the bouncer told us to leave. We were confused, since we hadn't even gotten a chance to show him our IDs. (We all had valid passports and/or state IDs ) We tried to ask him why but he kept telling us to get out and that we're "tresspassing". The rest of the staff was watching but no one stepped in or said anything. The bouncers attitude was hostile and condescending. We couldn't understand why we were being denied entry, and it felt like we were being racially profiled. We tried to call their manager but they didn't put us through, and said "you want an explanation for what happened? Well you won't get it". Honestly I don't understand how this place is still standing in 2019. I wouldn't recommend this place to anyone, especially if you are a person of color. Our experience was just hurtful and shocking. Being denied entry is one thing, and not giving us a reason or a justification Is another. I hope no one else shares a similar experience but I doubt that they will change, considering the attitude of the people working there.

I felt humiliated. (With Photos)  So it was my birthday two months ago and I've always wanted to visit this place every since I saw it when I moved to Chicago.  I finally got the chance tonight to visit after clearing my schedule! The bouncer stopped me immediately and I felt a sense of anger from him. He asked to see my ID, of course, I produced it it to him. He said "the print looks all off and that it wasn't like other Michigan ID's, I'm not accepting it- do you have a passport?". I did not have one. He went to the waitress and started talking to her and I felt embarrassed to even be there, as he was started talking and looking directly at me. I wanted to just not be there. I wanted to find a way so bad to prove I was even my age- I know I look young, and I've been looked down my entire life and not taken seriously because of it, and this was just another low blow for me. He was so rude, aggressively insulting because of how I appeared- that I was "faking my age" , I've never had someone humiliate me like that in my life. On my way out- he said "bye" in a really sarcastic tone like he just squashed a bug, at that moment I was really disappointed.  Please management; talk to your bouncers. There are people that really are of age that are being discriminated against, and given a really mean attitude for no clear reason or explanation.  I'm also not the only one to be given this treatment... this clearly a reoccurring problem, check out some of the other reviews I found. Yikes!

This was confusing because everywhere else we have dined in Chicago has done free refills. When it came, the glass was completely filled with ice and the Coke was very watery.  Then there was the food. We had the calamari and the chicken sandwich. Both were flavourless.  We mentioned to the waiter when ordering that we were in a bit of a rush.
